For "swipe to dismiss" / "sweep away" list animations, the perceived motion depends almost entirely on the timing of the OPACITY fade relative to the TRANSFORM translate. If they run in parallel with similar durations, the user sees "fade in place" — by the time the row is halfway across, it's already mostly invisible.

The pattern that reads as physical motion (used by iOS Mail, Gmail mobile, Material list dismiss): hold opacity at 1.0 for the first 55-60% of the animation while the transform translates visibly, then fade only in the latter third. The eye locks onto the motion before anything fades.

A CSS `transition` cannot express this — every transitioned property goes start→end with a single delay, so you can only stagger by delays, not insert keyframe stops. Use `@keyframes` instead. Animation occupies a separate cascade layer from `transition`, which means it also doesn't conflict with sibling state-class `transition` shorthands (e.g. a `.just-completed` class with `transition: border-color, box-shadow` won't clobber the swipe).

Proven curve from this project (verified in live browser via Playwright sampling):
```
@keyframes swipe-out {
  0%   { transform: translate3d(0, 0, 0);    opacity: 1; }
  35%  { transform: translate3d(8%, 0, 0);   opacity: 1; }
  55%  { transform: translate3d(28%, 0, 0);  opacity: 1; }
  85%  { transform: translate3d(85%, 0, 0);  opacity: 0.35; }
  100% { transform: translate3d(118%, 0, 0); opacity: 0; }
}
.row.is-swiping-out {
  animation: swipe-out 720ms cubic-bezier(0.55, 0.06, 0.68, 0.19) forwards;
  pointer-events: none;
  will-change: transform, opacity;
}
```
Sampled timeline: 100ms → 1.0 opacity, +6px; 400ms → 1.0 opacity, +232px; 550ms → 0.79 opacity, +512px; 700ms → 0.24 opacity, +1050px. Use `cubic-bezier(0.55, 0.06, 0.68, 0.19)` (aggressive ease-in) so the row "flicks" off the list — feels like it's being thrown.

Companion pattern: trigger via JS by adding the class imperatively BEFORE removing the item from data, await the duration (sleep just longer than the animation — 720ms anim → wait 760ms), then remove. Don't use Vue's TransitionGroup leave for the swipe itself — the leave classes have low specificity and lose to sibling state classes that set the `transition` shorthand. Use leave only for the height collapse afterward.

Don't reach for a JS animation library (Motion, GSAP, anime.js) for a single-element swipe — keyframes are the right tool, hardware-accelerated, declarative, and free.

For Vue 3 list-mutation animations (add/remove/reorder), reach for `@formkit/auto-animate` rather than fighting Vue's `<TransitionGroup>` or hand-rolled CSS keyframes. It's 5KB, zero-config for the simple case, and exposes a plugin function API for full keyframe control:

```ts
import { useAutoAnimate } from '@formkit/auto-animate/vue';

const [listRef] = useAutoAnimate<HTMLOListElement>((el, action, oldCoords, newCoords) => {
  if (action === 'add')    return new KeyframeEffect(el, [...], { duration, easing, fill: 'both' });
  if (action === 'remove') return new KeyframeEffect(el, [...], { duration, easing, fill: 'both' });
  // 'remain' — FLIP-style move when neighbors shift
  const dx = (oldCoords?.left ?? 0) - (newCoords?.left ?? 0);
  const dy = (oldCoords?.top ?? 0) - (newCoords?.top ?? 0);
  return new KeyframeEffect(el, [
    { transform: `translate(${dx}px, ${dy}px)` },
    { transform: 'translate(0, 0)' },
  ], { duration: 420, easing: 'cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1)', fill: 'both' });
});
```

Then in the template: `<ol ref="listRef">...</ol>` (regular element, NOT TransitionGroup).

Why this beats the alternatives:
- **vs TransitionGroup**: TransitionGroup's leave classes (.foo-leave-active etc.) have specificity 0,1,0 and silently lose to any sibling state class with higher specificity that sets a `transition` shorthand. Hours of debugging that. AutoAnimate runs Web Animations API directly on the element — no CSS cascade involvement.
- **vs hand-rolled CSS @keyframes + imperative class toggling**: AutoAnimate handles the lifecycle: re-inserts the leaving DOM node with `position: absolute`, plays the animation, then removes it. You don't have to time `setTimeout`s before refresh, you don't have to manage ref state for "currently animating" items, you don't have to coordinate with FLIP for the rows below.
- **vs heavier libraries (GSAP, Motion)**: AutoAnimate's API is one composable + a plugin function. No separate timeline objects, no scroll triggers, just list mutations.

CRITICAL gotchas:
1. **`prefers-reduced-motion` is bypassed when config is a plugin function** (auto-animate/index.mjs L721-723: `isDisabledDueToReduceMotion = mediaQuery.matches && !isPlugin(config) && !config.disrespectUserMotionPreference`). When using the options-object path you must explicitly opt out via `disrespectUserMotionPreference: true` if you want animations to play for reduced-motion users. The plugin path is implicitly disrespect=true. This often EXPLAINS reports of "your animation works for you but not for the user" — the user has reduced-motion enabled in their OS (Windows: Settings → Accessibility → Visual effects → Animation effects).
2. **Use `useAutoAnimate` composable, not `autoAnimate(el, plugin)` in onMounted**, when the list is inside a v-if/conditional branch. At onMounted time the element ref may be null; the composable handles late-mount via reactive ref binding.
3. **Don't double-call `autoAnimate`**: each call sets up a fresh MutationObserver, and the second observer interferes with the first (animations fire twice, animations.set overwrites). One call only.
4. **Plugin call signature varies by action**: AutoAnimate calls `plugin(el, 'add', newCoords)`, `plugin(el, 'remove', oldCoords)`, `plugin(el, 'remain', oldCoords, newCoords)` — the third positional argument is NOT always "newCoords" despite the TypeScript type. For `remove` it's `oldCoords`. Type your plugin's third arg as the union and use it situationally.

Animation curve guidance for swipe-to-dismiss (verified empirically in live browser):
- Distribute keyframes so transform is visibly progressing by 25% offset (e.g. translate3d(22%, ...) at offset 0.25). An aggressive ease-in alone leaves the row "stuck" for 300ms+ and reads as instant-disappear.
- Hold opacity at 1 until offset 0.5+ so the eye locks onto motion before fading.
- Use Material standard easing `cubic-bezier(0.4, 0.0, 0.2, 1)` for a smooth swipe; reserve aggressive ease-in (cubic-bezier(0.55, 0.06, 0.68, 0.19)) only when paired with strongly distributed keyframes.

When debugging "the animation isn't working", inspect the parent's `getComputedStyle().position`: AutoAnimate sets it to `relative` at attachment time if the original was `static`. If it's still `static`, AutoAnimate didn't attach.
